text:
Assuming this is a non-rhetorical question : the key to any business being defined as a startup would be "*fast rate of growth over relatively small time frame*". There's no objective way of defining fast and small here (ex: consumer technology startups have been measured on their % growth rates at daily/weekly metrics, SaaS startups typically on monthly metrics)
 but a typical business would have 3 phases growth wise
• start as a hypothesis with slow/no growth till it achieves a semblance of what to build & who to build for (or dies in that process :man-shrugging::skin-tone-2:)
• hyper growth once it finds the two, and improves on its ability to reach a larger market - a true startup :seedling:
• slowing/plateauing growth as it reaches saturation due to external/internal reasons, at which point it surely ceases being a startup :evergreen_tree:

text: When they stop being nimble. Unlike others, I think revenue growth rate has nothing to do with being a “startup”. You can be waddling fiercely under the water yet see no movement on the top. That is still very much a startup in my books, constantly reiterating, constantly course-correcting, constantly improving. Revenue and revenue growth is an outcome that may or may not happen. Having started up before, I was in a situation where I was fiercely trying to succeed yet failing to see revenue outcomes I wanted. Was I not a startup since I had no 3x revenue growth? Would aggressively and vehemently disagree :laughing:
